{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"fields":{"description":"# Publish the review policy: what the LLM-Review and Verified gates mean for contributors\n\n## Why\n\nrebar's blocking `LLM-Review` Gerrit label appears to be first-of-kind in public OSS: research (2024–2026) found no project documenting a blocking LLM merge vote — the Kubernetes AI-review policy (https://github.com/kubernetes/community/blob/master/github-management/ai-code-review-tools.md) makes AI review advisory-only. Novelty raises the documentation bar. The document's SHAPE is convergent: Chromium's CQ doc (https://chromium.googlesource.com/chromium/src/+/main/docs/infra/cq.md) and Zuul's gating doc (https://zuul-ci.org/docs/zuul/latest/gating.html) both name the labels, define each vote value, state bot-vs-human authority, and document escape hatches.\n\nWhy a separate doc rather than expanding CONTRIBUTING §2c (which already sketches the two votes): §2c is the in-flow quick reference; the policy doc carries the normative content (authority, dispute, bypass, responsibility) that outlives workflow edits and is linkable from every other surface. Authority rule recorded in both files: `docs/review-policy.md` is authoritative for vote semantics; §2c becomes a summary + pointer (this story slims §2c accordingly — the epic's single-source rule).\n\n## What\n\nNew `docs/review-policy.md` (contributor-facing):\n\n- The two required labels, described accurately:\n  - `Verified` — CI on GitHub Actions via `gerrit-verify.yaml`. Do NOT describe it as just `make lint && make typecheck && make test`: the workflow additionally runs the rebar-ticket trailer check, module-size gate, prompt-index/env-registry drift gates, security-rules freshness, criteria-routing parity, public-types drift, `make config-check`, pip-audit, and unit + integration pytest tiers. The doc states: \"locally approximate with `make lint && make typecheck && make test`; the authoritative list is the workflow file (linked).\"\n  - `LLM-Review` — what the bot reviews, and that only bots/admins vote either label (no self-approval, no self-verification).\n- Vote-semantics table (Chromium style), sourced from the authoritative enum `_TAG_SUFFIXES` in `src/rebar/review_bot/adapter.py` — all FIVE coverage-gap sub-reasons (gate-disabled, llm-unavailable, scanner, review-error, indeterminate) plus the `(merge-change, N integrated commit(s))` suffix variant emitted on merge paths (voter.py). Each row: what it means + the productive response (`finding` → fix and re-push; `coverage-gap (…)` → infra veto, not your code, maintainer re-triggers; `Verified −1` → open the linked run; `recheck` for flakes). Add a one-line drift guard note in the doc: \"if you see a tag not listed here, treat it as coverage-gap-class and ping the maintainer\" (the enum is small and stable; a CI drift gate is out of scope v1).\n- Bot vs human authority (Zuul's mechanical-enforcement framing): (a) the lead maintainer sets the rubric and can waive/override any finding; (b) dispute path — resolve the comment thread with written justification or raise to the maintainer, who responds best-effort within 5 business days (matching SECURITY.md's ack window); if unresolved, the maintainer's decision is final (solo-maintainer reality, stated plainly); (c) the gate supplements maintainer judgment; (d) bypasses are admin-only and auditable.\n- Responsibility clause (Kubernetes norm, cited): the submitter must be able to personally explain their change, AI-assisted or not.\n- One clarifying paragraph distinguishing THIS (code-review merge gate) from the plan-review ticket gate, linking docs/plan-review-gate.md.\n- Framing recorded in the doc itself: the gate is \"required-with-human-override\"; the dispute path is v1 and will iterate with the first external contributor.\n\nLinks this story owns (ownership-inversion rule — the tutorial exists first; this story depends_on it): add the review-policy link into CONTRIBUTING.md §2c (slimmed to summary+pointer) and retarget `docs/your-first-change.md`'s vote-semantics link from §2c to the new doc.\n\n## Scope\n\nIN: `docs/review-policy.md` (new), CONTRIBUTING §2c slim-down + pointer, tutorial link retarget.\nOUT: changing gate behavior/thresholds/criteria; a CI drift gate tying the doc to `_TAG_SUFFIXES` (noted as future work); the plan-review gate's own docs; Gerrit ACL changes.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] `docs/review-policy.md` present — prove: greps for both label names, all five coverage-gap sub-reasons + \"merge-change\", \"recheck\", \"5 business days\", \"plan-review\" (the distinction paragraph), and the override/dispute/bypass sections.\n- [ ] Verified is described via the workflow, not the three-command shorthand — prove: the doc links `gerrit-verify.yaml` and labels `make lint/typecheck/test` as a local approximation.\n- [ ] No-self-approval and maintainer-override both stated — prove: grep.\n- [ ] Single-source enforced — prove: CONTRIBUTING §2c contains a pointer to review-policy.md and no longer carries the full sub-reason enumeration; `docs/your-first-change.md` links review-policy.md.\n- [ ] The required-with-human-override framing + v1-iteration caveat appear in the doc."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783631031260901001,"uuid":"422eba9a-3230-4a74-9552-34729168825d"}